## If Statements and Blocks

In the previous lesson (Control flow introduction) you saw that C++ gives you several tools to redirect program flow. The most fundamental is the **if statement**, which executes a branch only when a condition is `true`.

### Basic syntax

```cpp
if (condition) {
    // runs when condition is true
} else {
    // runs when condition is false
}
```

The condition is any expression that evaluates to `bool`. Unlike Python, the parentheses around the condition are **required** in C++.

### Blocks matter

A *block* is a sequence of statements wrapped in `{}`. Without braces, only the very next statement belongs to the `if`:

```cpp
int score = 85;
if (score >= 90)
    std::cout << "A\n";   // part of if
    std::cout << "Great!"; // always runs — easy bug!
```

Always use braces. They make intent explicit and prevent the dangling-else class of bugs. This is especially important when adding statements later.

### Chaining conditions

Use `else if` to test a sequence of mutually exclusive cases:

```cpp
int score = 72;
if (score >= 90) {
    std::cout << "A\n";
} else if (score >= 80) {
    std::cout << "B\n";
} else if (score >= 70) {
    std::cout << "C\n";
} else {
    std::cout << "Below C\n";
}
// Output: C
```

C++ evaluates each condition top-to-bottom and executes **only the first matching branch**, then skips the rest — identical to Python's `elif` chain.

### Nested if statements

You can place an `if` inside another `if`'s block. Keep nesting shallow (two levels max is a good rule) to preserve readability. Consider early returns or combining conditions with `&&` / `||` when nesting grows deep.

### Common pitfalls

- **Assignment vs. comparison:** `if (x = 5)` assigns 5 and is always true. Use `if (x == 5)`. Enable `-Wall` warnings — the compiler will catch this.
- **Implicit bool conversion:** integers convert to `bool` (`0` is `false`, anything else is `true`), but prefer explicit comparisons for clarity.
- **Dangling else:** when braces are omitted, an `else` attaches to the nearest `if`, which may not be the one you intended.

### Key takeaways

- Always wrap `if`/`else` bodies in `{}`.
- `else if` chains are evaluated in order; only the first match executes.
- Nested conditions are fine in small doses; flatten them when they grow unwieldy.

