## Switch Statement Basics

In the previous lessons you used `if`/`else if` chains to branch on conditions. When you are testing **one variable against several constant values**, a `switch` statement is cleaner and often faster.

### Anatomy of a switch

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    int day{3};
    switch (day) {
        case 1:  std::cout << "Monday\n";    break;
        case 2:  std::cout << "Tuesday\n";   break;
        case 3:  std::cout << "Wednesday\n"; break;
        default: std::cout << "Other\n";     break;
    }
}
```

**Key parts:**

- **`switch (expression)`** — the expression must produce an integral or enumeration type (e.g. `int`, `char`, `enum`). Unlike Python's `match`, you cannot switch on a `std::string`.
- **`case N:`** — a label that the compiler jumps to when the expression equals `N`. The value after `case` must be a compile-time constant (same idea as the `constexpr if` values from lesson 8-4).
- **`break`** — exits the switch body. **If you omit `break`, execution falls through to the next case label** — a common source of bugs (your compiler warns with `-Wfallthrough`).
- **`default:`** — optional catch-all, like the final `else` in an `if`/`else if` chain (lesson 8-2). Place it last; some style guides require it even when all cases are covered.

### Fallthrough — intentional vs accidental

Fallthrough is occasionally useful (grouping several cases that share code), but you must signal intent with `[[fallthrough]]` to silence the warning:

```cpp
case 'a':
case 'e':  // empty case — falls through intentionally
    ++vowels;
    break;
```

Empty cases like `case 'a':` above fall through silently; the attribute is only needed when a non-empty case intentionally falls into the next.

### Switch vs if/else

| Situation | Prefer |
|---|---|
| One variable, many constant values | `switch` |
| Range checks (`x > 10`) | `if`/`else` |
| String comparisons | `if`/`else` (or `std::map`) |

### Declaring variables inside switch

You cannot declare an initialized variable in one case and use it in another without wrapping the case body in braces `{}` — the compiler rejects it to avoid jumping over initialization, similar to the block-scope rules from lesson 8-2.

Next up: goto statements (and why you almost never use them).

