## Switch Fallthrough and Scoping

In the previous lesson you saw how a `switch` statement jumps to a matching `case` label. What happens *after* that case runs? By default, execution **falls through** -- it keeps running into the next case without checking it. This is unlike Python's `match` statement, which stops automatically.

```cpp
#include <iostream>
int main() {
    int x { 2 };
    switch (x) {
        case 1: std::cout << "one\n";   // skipped
        case 2: std::cout << "two\n";   // matches, runs
        case 3: std::cout << "three\n"; // also runs (fallthrough!)
        default: std::cout << "done\n"; // also runs
    }
}
// Output: two  three  done
```

Fallthrough is almost always a bug. Fix it by ending every case with `break` (or `return` inside a function). The compiler warns about implicit fallthrough with `-Wextra`.

### Intentional fallthrough with `[[fallthrough]]`

Sometimes fallthrough is deliberate -- for example, when two values share identical handling. C++17 introduced the `[[fallthrough]]` attribute to silence the compiler warning and signal intent clearly:

```cpp
case 2:
    [[fallthrough]]; // intentional -- fall into case 3
case 3:
    std::cout << "two or three\n";
    break;
```

Always use `[[fallthrough]]` when you mean it. A bare implicit fallthrough is a red flag in code review.

### Variable declarations inside switch

A `switch` body is one big compound statement. A variable declared in one `case` is technically in scope for *all* subsequent cases -- but only initialised if that case runs. Jumping past an initialisation is illegal in C++ (unlike C):

```cpp
switch (x) {
    case 1:
        int val { 42 }; // ERROR if case 2 is reachable -- jumps past init
        break;
    case 2:
        std::cout << val; // val is in scope but was never initialised
}
```

The fix is to wrap each case in **braces** to give it its own scope:

```cpp
switch (x) {
    case 1: { int val { 42 }; std::cout << val; break; }
    case 2: { int val { 7 };  std::cout << val; break; }
}
```

Braces in cases are a best practice whenever you need local variables. They also keep cases visually self-contained, echoing the block discipline from the "If statements and blocks" lesson.

