## Break and Continue

Two keywords — `break` and `continue` — give you extra control over loop execution. You've already seen `break` used in `switch` statements (lesson 8-5); it works the same way inside loops.

### break — Exit the loop early

`break` immediately terminates the nearest enclosing loop (or `switch`) and jumps to the first statement after it. Use it when you've found what you were looking for and continuing would waste work.

```cpp
#include <iostream>

int main() {
    // Find the first number in [1, 100] divisible by both 7 and 11
    for (int i { 1 }; i <= 100; ++i) {
        if (i % 7 == 0 && i % 11 == 0) {
            std::cout << "Found: " << i << '\n'; // prints 77
            break; // no need to keep going
        }
    }
    return 0;
}
```

`break` only exits **one** level of nesting. If you have nested loops and need to exit both, a common C++ pattern is to use a flag variable, or to extract the inner loop into a function and `return` from it.

### continue — Skip the rest of this iteration

`continue` skips the remainder of the current loop body and jumps straight to the loop's update expression (in a `for` loop) or condition check (in a `while`/`do-while` loop). The loop itself keeps running.

Use `continue` when a particular iteration has nothing useful to do, rather than nesting the rest of the body inside an `if`.

```cpp
// Print odd numbers from 1 to 10 (without continue the body would need an extra if)
for (int i { 1 }; i <= 10; ++i) {
    if (i % 2 == 0) continue; // skip even numbers
    std::cout << i << ' ';    // 1 3 5 7 9
}
```

### When to use each

| Goal | Keyword |
|---|---|
| Stop the loop completely | `break` |
| Skip only this iteration | `continue` |

Both keywords make loops easier to read **when used sparingly**. Overusing them — especially `continue` deep inside complex loops — can make control flow hard to follow. Prefer them over deeply nested `if` chains, but reach for a named function or an early `return` when the logic grows large.

Note: unlike Python's `for`/`else` construct, C++ has no loop `else`. Any "nothing found" logic must go after the loop using a flag or a sentinel value.

